"Davenport J.","Temperature and the life-history strategies of sea turtles",1997,"Journal of Thermal Biology","22","6",,"479","488",,,10.1016/S0306-4565(97)00066-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031462226&partnerID=40&md5=e1a56677e012cfb6a411cd6938b696f2","Univ. Mar. Biol. Station Millport, Isle of Cumbrae KA28 0EG, United Kingdom","Davenport, J., Univ. Mar. Biol. Station Millport, Isle of Cumbrae KA28 0EG, United Kingdom","1. Sea turtles have a high fecundity, high mortality, great longevity life history strategy. 2. With the exception of the leatherback, turtle distribution is constrained by the 20°C surface isotherm. 3. All sea turtles exhibit temperature-dependent sex determination (TSD) with pivotal temperatures close to 29°C. 4. It is suggested that hatchling sex ratio will vary chaotically because of TSD. 5. Because of TSD and natal homing, sea turtles are likely to be adversely affected by global warming. 6. TSD and global warming have implications for conservation/management of sea turtles.","Chaos; Global warming; Sea turtles; Temperature; Temperature-dependent sex determination",,,,,,,"Ackerman, R.A., The nest environment and the embryonic development of sea turtles (1997) The Biology of Sea Turtles, pp. 83-106. , ed. P. L. Lutz and J. A. Musick. CRC Press, Boca Raton; Bleakney, J.S., Reports of marine turtles from New England and eastern Canada (1965) Canadian Field Naturalist, 79, pp. 120-128; Birse, R., Davenport, J., Gut action in young loggerhead turtles Caretta caretta L (1987) Herpetological Journal, 1, pp. 170-175; Bjorndal, K.A., Bolten, A.B., Growth rates of immature green turtles, Chelonia mydas, on feeding grounds in the southern Bahamas (1988) Copeia, 1988, pp. 555-564; Bolten, A.B., Bjorndal, K.A., Grumbles, J.S., Owens, D.W., Sex ratio and sex-specific growth rates of immature green turtles, Chelonia mydas, in the southern Bahamas (1992) Copeia, 1992, pp. 1098-1103; Bowen, B.W., Nelson, W.S., Avise, J.C., A molecular p